One of four men taken before the consul at Constantinople for misdemeanours and failure to work. The men refused to return to the ship and work and were therefore imprisoned. There are extensive complaints in the ship's log about these four men.

James Maxwell claimed to be seaman with 9 years' experience, but "he proved immediately after coming to sea to be a landsman". He was only able to name 16 of the ship's 150 ropes. After much frustration of the master, he was set menial tasks and his wages much reduced. He later admitted that he lived outside of Greenock and had his own house, a wife and three children in the highlands. He had not seen them lately, but had been employed as a candlemaker. He got advice from the boarding master as to how to be taken on as crew.

Long tale in the log of Grube's illness. He was unable to work for long periods but tried to conceal the nature of his disease, which appears to have been gonorrhea. Treated by a Greek doctor but after taking some medicine refused to take more saying the doctor intended to poison him. Eventually the crew became fed up with his lack of work and notified the master of the nature of his disease. He had intended to conceal as much as he could in order to continued being paid and then attempt to find a cure in England. However his wages were stopped when the situation became clear.

1. Suffered from ague at Ibrail (Modern Braila, Romania). "Doses of opening medicine and quinine were administered". 2.Was descending from the main top and more than half way down when he fell into the water. Lines were thrown out to him, but he did not seem to notice them. The ship was turned around and drifted back to him, but although the ship passed around 3 yards from him, "he appeared motionless and sinking and was seen no more".

Indentured 1868-02-01, Cardiff. Went ashore at Antwerp without permission. He had "strouled (sic) about the town and became entangled between the railway waggons and was killed". "He has been often warned , and once punished, for leaving the ship at night, without liberty". A list of his effects and wages due is recorded.
1871-07-20, 20 miles east of Gibraltar. Fell from mast head to the deck. Insensible for a few seconds but recovered. Sore back and thigh, but apparently no fractures.

Much complaint in the ship's log about Robert Jackson being unable to work due to veneral disease contracted before leaving England. Eventually hospitalised and discharged at Porto Torres and advised to proceed to Leghorn (Livorno) by steamer.
